@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{simple-extras.el} extends Emacs's built-in @samp{simple.el} library with a systematic set of editing primitives, mode enhancements, and utility functions. While @samp{simple.el} provides the foundational commands for killing, yanking, transposing, and indenting text, it does not offer corresponding @emph{delete} (remove without touching the kill ring) or @emph{copy} (add to the kill ring without removing) variants. This package fills that gap.

The core design principle is straightforward: for every standard @samp{kill-*} command that operates on a text object (word, line, sentence, paragraph, or sexp), @samp{simple-extras.el} provides a matching @samp{delete-*} variant that discards the text and a @samp{copy-*} variant that saves it to the kill ring without removing it from the buffer. It also provides @samp{kill-whole-*}, @samp{delete-whole-*}, and @samp{copy-whole-*} commands that operate on the entire text object at point, and backward @samp{transpose-*} commands that move text objects in the reverse direction.

Beyond editing primitives, @samp{simple-extras.el} offers several DWIM (Do What I Mean) commands: a smart @code{keyboard-quit} that adapts its behavior to the current context, an @code{indent-dwim} that indents the region, Org source block, or entire buffer, and a @code{narrow-or-widen-dwim} that toggles narrowing based on what is at point. Other utilities include text conversion via Pandoc, accent removal and slugification, enhanced mode toggling for @code{visible-mode} and @code{visual-line-mode}, and auto-save support for untitled buffers.

The package depends on @samp{no-littering} (for determining the auto-save directory) and @samp{paths} (for path constants).

