@node Word operations
@section Word operations

@findex simple-extras-delete-word
@findex simple-extras-backward-delete-word
@findex simple-extras-copy-word
@findex simple-extras-backward-copy-word
@findex simple-extras-kill-whole-word
@findex simple-extras-delete-whole-word
@findex simple-extras-copy-whole-word
@findex simple-extras-transpose-words-backward
Emacs's built-in @code{kill-word} and @code{backward-kill-word} always place the deleted text on the kill ring. This is often undesirable when you simply want to discard a word or copy it without disturbing the kill ring's contents. The word operation commands address this gap.

The command @code{simple-extras-delete-word} works like @code{kill-word} but discards the text without touching the kill ring. It accepts an optional numeric prefix argument to delete that many words forward. Its backward counterpart, @code{simple-extras-backward-delete-word}, deletes words behind point. Similarly, @code{simple-extras-copy-word} copies forward words to the kill ring without removing them from the buffer, and @code{simple-extras-backward-copy-word} does the same in the backward direction.

When you need to act on the entire word at point regardless of where point is within it, use @code{simple-extras-kill-whole-word} (kills and adds to kill ring), @code{simple-extras-delete-whole-word} (discards), or @code{simple-extras-copy-whole-word} (copies to kill ring without removing). These commands use @code{bounds-of-thing-at-point} internally to determine the word boundaries (@ref{Operating on the whole text object}).

The command @code{simple-extras-transpose-words-backward} interchanges the word before point with the one before it, effectively the reverse of the standard @code{transpose-words}. This is useful when you realize two words are in the wrong order and want to fix it by moving the current word backward rather than forward.

@node Line operations
@section Line operations

@findex simple-extras-delete-line
@findex simple-extras-backward-delete-line
@findex simple-extras-copy-line
@findex simple-extras-backward-copy-line
@findex simple-extras-kill-whole-line
@findex simple-extras-delete-whole-line
@findex simple-extras-copy-whole-line
@findex simple-extras-transpose-lines-backward
The line commands mirror the word commands in structure (@ref{Word operations}). The command @code{simple-extras-delete-line} deletes from point to the end of the line (or ARG lines forward with a prefix argument) without touching the kill ring. The command @code{simple-extras-backward-delete-line} deletes from point to the beginning of the line.

The command @code{simple-extras-copy-line} copies from point to the end of the line (or ARG lines forward) to the kill ring without removing the text. The command @code{simple-extras-backward-copy-line} copies backward to the beginning of the line.

For whole-line operations, @code{simple-extras-kill-whole-line} kills the entire line at point, @code{simple-extras-delete-whole-line} deletes it without the kill ring, and @code{simple-extras-copy-whole-line} copies it. These are particularly useful when bound to key sequences for quick line manipulation.

The command @code{simple-extras-transpose-lines-backward} exchanges the current line with the previous one, the reverse of @code{transpose-lines}. This provides a natural way to move a line upward in a buffer.

@node Sentence operations
@section Sentence operations

@findex simple-extras-delete-sentence
@findex simple-extras-backward-delete-sentence
@findex simple-extras-copy-sentence
@findex simple-extras-backward-copy-sentence
@findex simple-extras-kill-whole-sentence
@findex simple-extras-delete-whole-sentence
@findex simple-extras-copy-whole-sentence
@findex simple-extras-transpose-sentences-backward
The sentence commands follow the same pattern as word and line operations (@ref{Word operations}). The command @code{simple-extras-delete-sentence} deletes forward to the end of the current sentence without touching the kill ring; with a negative prefix argument, it deletes backward. The command @code{simple-extras-backward-delete-sentence} deletes backward to the start of the sentence.

The copy variants, @code{simple-extras-copy-sentence} and @code{simple-extras-backward-copy-sentence}, add the sentence text to the kill ring without removing it from the buffer.

The whole-sentence commands (@code{simple-extras-kill-whole-sentence}, @code{simple-extras-delete-whole-sentence}, @code{simple-extras-copy-whole-sentence}) act on the entire sentence at point. The command @code{simple-extras-transpose-sentences-backward} swaps the current sentence with the previous one.

@node Paragraph operations
@section Paragraph operations

@findex simple-extras-delete-paragraph
@findex simple-extras-backward-delete-paragraph
@findex simple-extras-copy-paragraph
@findex simple-extras-backward-copy-paragraph
@findex simple-extras-kill-whole-paragraph
@findex simple-extras-delete-whole-paragraph
@findex simple-extras-copy-whole-paragraph
@findex simple-extras-transpose-paragraphs-backward
The paragraph commands complete the set of text-object operations (@ref{Word operations}). The command @code{simple-extras-delete-paragraph} deletes forward to the end of the paragraph; with prefix argument N, it deletes to the Nth paragraph end. A negative argument deletes backward. The command @code{simple-extras-backward-delete-paragraph} deletes backward to the start of the paragraph.

The copy variants (@code{simple-extras-copy-paragraph} and @code{simple-extras-backward-copy-paragraph}) add paragraph text to the kill ring without removing it. The whole-paragraph commands (@code{simple-extras-kill-whole-paragraph}, @code{simple-extras-delete-whole-paragraph}, @code{simple-extras-copy-whole-paragraph}) operate on the entire paragraph at point.

The command @code{simple-extras-transpose-paragraphs-backward} swaps the current paragraph with the previous one.

@node Sexp operations
@section Sexp operations

@findex simple-extras-delete-sexp
@findex simple-extras-backward-delete-sexp
@findex simple-extras-copy-sexp
@findex simple-extras-backward-copy-sexp
@findex simple-extras-kill-whole-sexp
@findex simple-extras-delete-whole-sexp
@findex simple-extras-copy-whole-sexp
@findex simple-extras-transpose-sexps-backward
The sexp (S-expression) commands are especially useful in Emacs Lisp and other Lisp dialects, where sexps are the fundamental unit of code structure. They follow the same delete/copy/kill-whole/transpose pattern as the other text-object commands (@ref{Word operations}).

The command @code{simple-extras-delete-sexp} deletes the next sexp (or ARG sexps) without affecting the kill ring. The command @code{simple-extras-backward-delete-sexp} does the same in the backward direction. The copy variants (@code{simple-extras-copy-sexp} and @code{simple-extras-backward-copy-sexp}) add sexp text to the kill ring without deleting it.

The whole-sexp commands (@code{simple-extras-kill-whole-sexp}, @code{simple-extras-delete-whole-sexp}, @code{simple-extras-copy-whole-sexp}) operate on the complete sexp at point. The command @code{simple-extras-transpose-sexps-backward} reverses the order of the two sexps around point.

@node Zap-to-char variants
@section Zap-to-char variants

@findex simple-extras-backward-zap-to-char
@findex simple-extras-zap-copy-to-char
@findex simple-extras-backward-zap-copy-to-char
@findex simple-extras-zap-delete-to-char
@findex simple-extras-backward-zap-delete-to-char
Emacs's built-in @code{zap-to-char} kills text from point up to and including a specified character. The commands in this group provide backward, copy, and delete variants of this operation.

The command @code{simple-extras-backward-zap-to-char} kills backward from point to the ARGth occurrence of a character. It prompts for the target character interactively and respects @code{case-fold-search}. Upper-case characters trigger a case-sensitive search when called interactively.

The command @code{simple-extras-zap-copy-to-char} copies text from point forward to the ARGth occurrence of a character, adding it to the kill ring without removing it from the buffer. The command @code{simple-extras-backward-zap-copy-to-char} does the same in the backward direction.

The command @code{simple-extras-zap-delete-to-char} deletes text from point forward to the ARGth occurrence of a character without touching the kill ring. The command @code{simple-extras-backward-zap-delete-to-char} does the same backward.

@node Character transposition
@section Character transposition

@findex simple-extras-transpose-chars-backward
The command @code{simple-extras-transpose-chars-backward} transposes the two characters around point, moving point backward by one character. This is the reverse of the standard @code{transpose-chars}, providing a quick way to fix transposition errors without repositioning point.

@node Smart region commands
@section Smart region commands

@findex simple-extras-smart-kill-region
@findex simple-extras-smart-delete-region
@findex simple-extras-smart-copy-region
These three commands provide DWIM behavior for acting on text: if the region is active, they operate on the region; otherwise, they operate on the whole current line. This makes them convenient as general-purpose bindings since they adapt to context.

The command @code{simple-extras-smart-kill-region} calls @code{kill-region} when the region is active, and @code{kill-whole-line} otherwise. The command @code{simple-extras-smart-delete-region} calls @code{delete-region} or @code{simple-extras-delete-whole-line} (@ref{Line operations}). The command @code{simple-extras-smart-copy-region} calls @code{copy-region-as-kill} or @code{simple-extras-copy-whole-line}.

@node Yank commands
@section Yank commands

@findex simple-extras-yank-and-pop
@findex simple-extras-paste-no-properties
The command @code{simple-extras-yank-and-pop} yanks the top entry from the kill ring and then removes that entry from the ring. This is useful when you want to paste something once and ensure it does not remain in the kill ring for accidental future yanks. After yanking, it displays a confirmation message.

The command @code{simple-extras-paste-no-properties} yanks the top of the kill ring with all text properties stripped. This is helpful when pasting text from formatted sources (such as web browsers or rich-text editors) into a plain-text buffer where font faces, colors, and other properties would be distracting.

@node Exchanging point and mark
@section Exchanging point and mark

@findex simple-extras-exchange-point-and-mark
The built-in @code{exchange-point-and-mark} swaps point and mark, but its interaction with @code{transient-mark-mode} can be surprising: without a prefix argument, it reactivates the mark even when the region was inactive, which is often not what you want. The command @code{simple-extras-exchange-point-and-mark} inverts the meaning of the prefix argument when transient mark mode is on but the region is inactive. This means calling it without a prefix argument in that situation will @emph{not} reactivate the mark, and calling it @emph{with} a prefix argument will.

This refinement, inspired by @uref{https://spwhitton.name/blog/entry/transient-mark-mode/, Sean Whitton's blog post}, makes @code{exchange-point-and-mark} more intuitive for users who rely on transient mark mode but frequently want to jump to the mark without activating a selection.

@node Enhanced visible mode
@section Enhanced visible mode

@findex simple-extras-visible-mode-enhanced
The command @code{simple-extras-visible-mode-enhanced} toggles @code{visible-mode} together with several related display modes, providing a single command to reveal or hide all visual embellishments at once. It accepts an optional prefix argument: positive to enable, negative to disable, or toggle if called interactively without an argument.

When in a Dired buffer, it also toggles @code{dired-hide-details-mode} and @code{dired-omit-mode}. When in an Org-mode buffer (including @code{org-agenda-mode} and @code{org-msg-mode}), it toggles @code{org-tidy-mode} (if present in @code{org-mode-hook}), inline images (via @code{org-extras-inline-images} from @samp{org-extras.el}), and @code{org-modern-mode} (when available and not in the agenda). This is useful for quickly switching between a ``clean'' reading view and a ``raw'' editing view.

@node Enhanced visual line mode
@section Enhanced visual line mode

@findex simple-extras-visual-line-mode-enhanced
The command @code{simple-extras-visual-line-mode-enhanced} toggles @code{visual-line-mode} while also managing the @code{truncate-lines} variable. When turning @code{visual-line-mode} off, it sets @code{truncate-lines} to @code{t} so long lines are truncated rather than wrapped. When turning it on, it sets @code{truncate-lines} to @code{nil}. This ensures consistent line-wrapping behavior that matches the user's intent when toggling visual line mode.

@node DWIM keyboard quit
@section DWIM keyboard quit

@findex simple-extras-keyboard-quit-dwim
The command @code{simple-extras-keyboard-quit-dwim} provides a context-aware replacement for the standard @code{keyboard-quit}. Instead of always calling @code{keyboard-quit}, it checks the current context and performs the most appropriate quit action:

@enumerate
@item
If the region is active, it deactivates the mark without adding the region to the window selection.
@item
If the Completions buffer is selected, it closes the completion window.
@item
If a prefix argument is pending, or a keyboard macro is being defined, it does nothing (or cancels the macro events).
@item
If the minibuffer is active, it hides any completions and then aborts the recursive edit.
@item
Otherwise, it falls through to the standard @code{keyboard-quit}.
@end enumerate

This behavior is inspired by @uref{https://protesilaos.com/emacs/dotemacs, Protesilaos Stavrou's configuration} and avoids the common annoyance of @code{keyboard-quit} disrupting ongoing macro definitions or unexpectedly clearing prefix arguments.

@node DWIM indentation
@section DWIM indentation

@findex simple-extras-indent-dwim
The command @code{simple-extras-indent-dwim} indents code intelligently based on context. If a region is active, it indents the region. If point is inside an Org source block (as determined by @code{org-in-src-block-p}), it narrows to the block and indents its contents. Otherwise, it indents the entire buffer.

In all cases, the command runs @code{whitespace-cleanup} afterward to remove trailing whitespace and fix other whitespace issues. This makes it a convenient one-stop command for keeping code properly formatted.

@node DWIM narrowing
@section DWIM narrowing

@findex simple-extras-narrow-or-widen-dwim
The command @code{simple-extras-narrow-or-widen-dwim} toggles narrowing based on the current context. If the buffer is already narrowed, it widens. Otherwise, it narrows to the first applicable target:

@enumerate
@item
The active region, if one is selected.
@item
An Org source block, if point is inside one (via @code{org-narrow-to-block}).
@item
An Org subtree and its children (via @code{org-extras-narrow-to-entry-and-children} from @samp{org-extras.el}).
@item
A Markdown subtree (via @code{markdown-narrow-to-subtree}), when in @code{markdown-mode}.
@item
A Ledger transaction (via @code{ledger-mode-extras-narrow-to-xact} from @samp{ledger-mode-extras.el}), when in @code{ledger-mode}.
@item
The current defun, as a fallback.
@end enumerate

This eliminates the need to remember separate narrowing commands for different contexts.

@node Word counting
@section Word counting

@findex simple-extras-count-words-dwim
The command @code{simple-extras-count-words-dwim} counts words in the active region if one exists, or in the current clipboard (kill ring) contents otherwise. Either way, the count is saved to the kill ring and displayed in the minibuffer. This is convenient when you need a quick word count for a selection or for text you have just copied.

@node Filling and unfilling
@section Filling and unfilling

@findex simple-extras-fill-or-unfill-paragraph
The command @code{simple-extras-fill-or-unfill-paragraph} acts like @code{fill-paragraph} on the first invocation, reformatting the current paragraph to respect @code{fill-column}. When called a second time in immediate succession, it @emph{unfills} the paragraph by setting @code{fill-column} to @code{point-max}, effectively joining all lines into one. This toggle behavior makes it easy to switch between filled and unfilled text with a single keybinding.

@node URL stripping
@section URL stripping

@findex simple-extras-strip-url
@findex simple-extras-strip-thing-at-point
The command @code{simple-extras-strip-url} simplifies the URL at point by removing the @samp{http(s)://} scheme, the @samp{www.} prefix, and any trailing slash. It replaces the URL in the buffer with the simplified version. If no URL is found at point, it signals an error.

The command @code{simple-extras-strip-thing-at-point} is a DWIM wrapper that dispatches to the appropriate stripping function based on the thing at point. Currently, it only supports URLs (delegating to @code{simple-extras-strip-url}) and collapses any surrounding whitespace afterward via @code{just-one-space}. This command is designed to be extended with additional thing types in the future.

Both commands rely on @code{simple-extras-get-url-at-point} to detect URLs and @code{simple-extras-simplify-url} to perform the simplification (@ref{URL utilities}).

@node Text conversion via Pandoc
@section Text conversion via Pandoc

@findex simple-extras-pandoc-convert
The command @code{simple-extras-pandoc-convert} converts text between formats using the external @uref{https://pandoc.org/, Pandoc} tool. It accepts a TARGET format (using Pandoc's format names), an optional SOURCE format (defaulting to HTML), and optional CONTENT (defaulting to the system clipboard).

When CONTENT is provided as a string, the conversion happens in a temporary buffer via @code{call-process-region}. When CONTENT is @code{nil}, the command reads from the system clipboard using @samp{pbv} (for HTML content) or @samp{pbpaste} (as a fallback), pipes it through Pandoc, and returns the result as a string. The @samp{--wrap=none} flag is always passed to prevent Pandoc from inserting line breaks.

This function is primarily used programmatically by other packages to convert clipboard HTML to Org or Markdown format.

@node Asciifying text
@section Asciifying text

@findex simple-extras-asciify-text
The command @code{simple-extras-asciify-text} removes accents and converts European language characters to their ASCII equivalents within a region. For example, ``cafe'' becomes ``cafe'', ``ss'' replaces ``ß'', and em dashes become double hyphens. When called interactively without a region, it operates on the current line.

The conversion table handles a wide range of characters including accented Latin characters (French, German, Spanish, Czech, Vietnamese, and others), special punctuation (soft hyphens, thin spaces, inverted question marks), and various dash types. The search is case-insensitive.

This command is used internally by @code{simple-extras-slugify} to prepare strings for URL slugification (@ref{Slugifying strings}).

@node Slugifying strings
@section Slugifying strings

@findex simple-extras-slugify
@findex simple-extras-slugify-clipboard
The command @code{simple-extras-slugify} converts a string into a URL-friendly slug: it strips Unicode punctuation, removes accents via @code{simple-extras-asciify-string} (@ref{Asciifying text}), converts to lowercase, and replaces spaces and underscores with hyphens. When called interactively, it prompts for a string, copies the resulting slug to the kill ring, and echoes it in the minibuffer.

The command @code{simple-extras-slugify-clipboard} is a convenience wrapper that takes the current clipboard (kill ring) content, slugifies it, and replaces the kill ring entry with the slug. This is useful for quickly converting a copied title or heading into a file-name-friendly format.

@node Sorting S-expressions
@section Sorting S-expressions

@findex simple-extras-sort-sexps
The command @code{simple-extras-sort-sexps} alphabetically sorts all S-expressions within the active region. It reads each sexp, sorts them by their string representation (ignoring leading whitespace and comments), and rewrites the region with the sorted order.

This is especially useful for keeping @code{use-package} declarations, @code{require} lists, or alist entries in a consistent alphabetical order. The command skips over comments attached to sexps, so inline documentation is preserved with its associated expression.

@node Removing advice
@section Removing advice

@findex simple-extras-advice-remove-all
The command @code{simple-extras-advice-remove-all} removes all advice functions from a given symbol. When called interactively, it prompts for a function name with completion. This is useful during development and debugging when you want to restore a function to its unadvised state without knowing exactly which advice functions were added.

@node Setting up a Python virtual environment
@section Setting up a Python virtual environment

@findex simple-extras-set-python-virtual-environment
The command @code{simple-extras-set-python-virtual-environment} creates a Python virtual environment in the root of the current Git repository. It locates the repository root via @code{locate-dominating-file}, names the virtual environment after the repository directory, and runs @samp{python -m venv} to create it. If the virtual environment already exists, it displays a message and takes no action. If the current buffer is not inside a Git repository, it signals an error.

