@node Editing macros
@section Editing macros

@findex simple-extras-delete-instead-of-kill
@findex simple-extras-copy-instead-of-kill
The macro @code{simple-extras-delete-instead-of-kill} evaluates its body forms with @code{kill-region} temporarily rebound to @code{delete-region}. This means any kill commands executed within the body will delete text without adding it to the kill ring. Nearly all of the @samp{delete-*} commands in this package are built on top of this macro (@ref{Word operations}, @ref{Line operations}, etc.).

The macro @code{simple-extras-copy-instead-of-kill} similarly rebinds @code{kill-region} to @code{kill-ring-save}, so that kill commands copy text to the kill ring without removing it from the buffer. It also sets @code{this-command} to @code{kill-region} to ensure proper interaction with the kill ring's append behavior. All @samp{copy-*} commands use this macro.

Both macros use @code{cl-letf} for the temporary rebinding, which ensures the original function is restored even if an error occurs.

@node Operating on the whole text object
@section Operating on the whole text object

@findex simple-extras-kill-whole-thing
The function @code{simple-extras-kill-whole-thing} kills the entire text object at point for a given THING type (such as @code{'word}, @code{'line}, @code{'sentence}, @code{'paragraph}, or @code{'sexp}). It uses @code{bounds-of-thing-at-point} to determine the boundaries of the text object and then calls @code{kill-region} on them. All @samp{kill-whole-*}, @samp{delete-whole-*}, and @samp{copy-whole-*} commands delegate to this function.

@node Save excursion with buffer restoration
@section Save excursion with buffer restoration

@findex simple-extras-save-excursion
The macro @code{simple-extras-save-excursion} works like the built-in @code{save-excursion} but additionally restores the original buffer if the body forms switch to a different buffer. The built-in @code{save-excursion} only saves and restores point and mark within the same buffer; if a @code{switch-to-buffer} call occurs in the body, point is not restored. This macro wraps its body in a @code{prog1} form that explicitly switches back to the original buffer and restores point.

@node URL utilities
@section URL utilities

@findex simple-extras-get-url-at-point
@findex simple-extras-remove-trailing-slash
@findex simple-extras-simplify-url
@findex simple-extras-get-url
@findex simple-extras-string-is-url-p
The function @code{simple-extras-get-url-at-point} attempts to extract a URL near point without moving point. It looks for URL-like character sequences, handles parentheses and whitespace boundaries, strips @samp{URL:} prefixes, removes trailing periods, and prepends @samp{http://} to bare @samp{www.} URLs. If no valid URL is found, it returns @code{nil}. An optional argument PT allows specifying a position other than point.

The function @code{simple-extras-remove-trailing-slash} strips a trailing slash from a string, and @code{simple-extras-simplify-url} removes the @samp{http(s)://} scheme, @samp{www.} prefix, and trailing slash from a URL string. These are used by @code{simple-extras-strip-url} (@ref{URL stripping}).

The function @code{simple-extras-get-url} retrieves a URL from multiple sources: an explicit argument, the current buffer's mode (EWW, Ebib, or Bib@TeX{}), or a user prompt pre-filled with the current kill ring entry. This provides a convenient way for other commands to obtain a URL regardless of context.

The function @code{simple-extras-string-is-url-p} checks whether a string is a valid URL by parsing it with @code{url-generic-parse-url} and verifying that both the scheme (@code{url-type}) and host (@code{url-host}) are present.

@node Asciifying strings
@section Asciifying strings

@findex simple-extras-asciify-string
The function @code{simple-extras-asciify-string} takes a string and returns a new string with all accented characters replaced by their ASCII equivalents. It works by inserting the string into a temporary buffer, calling @code{simple-extras-asciify-text} on it (@ref{Asciifying text}), and returning the result. This is used by @code{simple-extras-slugify} for programmatic accent removal (@ref{Slugifying strings}).

@node Slug helpers
@section Slug helpers

@findex simple-extras-slug-hyphenate
The function @code{simple-extras-slug-hyphenate} replaces spaces, underscores, and dots with hyphens in a string, collapses multiple consecutive hyphens into one, and strips leading and trailing hyphens. It is used internally by @code{simple-extras-slugify} (@ref{Slugifying strings}).

@node Network detection
@section Network detection

@findex simple-extras-connected-to-network-p
The function @code{simple-extras-connected-to-network-p} checks whether the system is connected to a specific WiFi network by name. On macOS, it queries the network SSID via @samp{ipconfig getsummary}; on GNU/Linux, it uses @samp{iwgetid -r}. It returns @code{t} if the current SSID matches the given NETWORK argument. This can be used in configuration to conditionally enable features that depend on being connected to a particular network (e.g., a home or office network).

@node Auto-save for new buffers
@section Auto-save for new buffers

@findex simple-extras-is-new-buffer-p
@findex simple-extras-new-buffer-enable-auto-save
@findex simple-extras-new-buffer-auto-save-dir
The function @code{simple-extras-is-new-buffer-p} returns @code{t} if the current buffer is a new, non-file-visiting buffer whose name starts with @samp{untitled}. This predicate is used by the auto-save infrastructure to identify buffers that need special handling.

The function @code{simple-extras-new-buffer-enable-auto-save} enables @code{auto-save-mode} for new buffers (as determined by @code{simple-extras-is-new-buffer-p}). It is added to @code{buffer-list-update-hook} so that auto-save is activated as soon as a new untitled buffer appears.

The function @code{simple-extras-new-buffer-auto-save-dir} is an @code{:around} advice on @code{auto-save-mode} that redirects auto-save files for untitled buffers to the directory specified by @code{simple-extras-new-buffer-auto-save-dir} (@ref{Auto-save directory for new buffers}). For file-visiting buffers, it passes through to the original function unchanged.

@node Miscellaneous utilities
@section Miscellaneous utilities

@findex simple-extras-init-disable-funs
@findex simple-extras-get-next-element
@findex simple-extras-call-verbosely
@findex simple-extras-get-emacs-distro
@findex simple-extras-string-at-point
@findex simple-extras-local-set-key
The function @code{simple-extras-init-disable-funs} disables a list of functions after a specified number of seconds by adding @code{ignore} as an @code{:override} advice. This can be used during Emacs startup to suppress unwanted function calls that occur during initialization.

The function @code{simple-extras-get-next-element} returns the next element in a list after a given element, cycling back to the first element when the end is reached. This is useful for implementing cycling behaviors in commands.

The function @code{simple-extras-call-verbosely} calls a function and displays a message with its name, optionally using a custom format string. This is useful for debugging or logging which functions are being called during complex operations.

The function @code{simple-extras-get-emacs-distro} detects whether the current Emacs build is the Mac port (@samp{emacs-mac}) or Emacs Plus (@samp{emacs-plus}) by checking for distribution-specific bound variables.

The function @code{simple-extras-string-at-point} returns the quote-delimited string at point by scanning forward and backward for string-syntax delimiters on the current line.

The function @code{simple-extras-local-set-key} binds a KEY to a COMMAND in the current buffer only, by creating a new sparse keymap with the current local map as its parent. This is useful for setting up buffer-specific keybindings from hooks or advice functions.

